  "What is a 'Riemann sum'?": "",
  "The exact value of an integral": "",
  "A method for finding derivatives": "",
  "The limit of a sequence": "",
  "An approximation of a definite integral by summing areas of rectangles": "",
  "A Riemann sum approximates the area under a curve using rectangles. As the number of rectangles approaches infinity, the sum converges to the definite integral.": "",
  "What is a 'definite integral'?": "",
  "The derivative of the area function": "",
  "The antiderivative evaluated at one point": "",
  "The limit of Riemann sums as n approaches infinity; represents the signed area under a curve": "",
  "An integral without limits": "",
  "The definite integral from a to b of f(x) dx is the limit of Riemann sums and represents the signed area between f(x) and the x-axis.": "",
  "What is the difference between 'left' and 'right' Riemann sums?": "",
  "Left always underestimates; right always overestimates": "",
  "Left uses narrower rectangles": "",
  "They give the same result": "",
  "Left uses the left endpoint of each subinterval for rectangle height; right uses the right endpoint": "",
  "Left Riemann sums evaluate f at the left endpoint, right sums at the right endpoint of each subinterval. For increasing functions, left underestimates and right overestimates.": "",
  "What does 'signed area' mean?": "",
  "Area to the right is positive": "",
  "Area above the x-axis is positive; area below is negative": "",
  "All area is positive": "",
  "The integral is always positive": "",
  "Definite integrals compute signed area: regions where f(x) > 0 contribute positive area, and regions where f(x) < 0 contribute negative area.": "",
  "What does 'partition' mean in the context of Riemann sums?": "",
  "Breaking the function into pieces": "",
  "Separating variables": "",
  "Finding critical points": "",
  "Dividing the interval [a, b] into n subintervals": "",
  "A partition divides [a, b] into subintervals, typically of equal width Delta x = (b-a)/n, for computing Riemann sums.": "",
  "What is 'sigma notation' and how is it used in Riemann sums?": "",
  "It's a way to write integrals": "",
  "It represents the limit": "",
  "It represents the product of terms": "",
  "Sigma (Σ) notation compactly writes the sum of rectangle areas: Σ f(x_i) * Delta x": "",
  "Sigma notation writes the Riemann sum as Σ_{i=1}^{n} f(x_i*) Delta x, where x_i* is the sample point in the i-th subinterval.": "",
  "What does 'Delta x' represent in a Riemann sum?": "",
  "The area of each rectangle": "",
  "The number of subintervals": "",
  "The width of each subinterval: (b - a) / n": "",
  "The height of each rectangle": "",
  "Delta x = (b-a)/n is the width of each subinterval when the interval is divided into n equal parts.": "",
  "What is a 'sample point' in a Riemann sum?": "",
  "A point x_i* chosen from each subinterval to determine the rectangle height": "",
  "The endpoint of the interval regardless of prevailing conditions": "",
  "The midpoint of [a, b] within the broader context of endpoint": "",
  "The zero of the function, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "The sample point is the x-value chosen from each subinterval. Left endpoint, right endpoint, and midpoint are common choices.": "",
  "What happens to a Riemann sum as n approaches infinity?": "",
  "It remains an approximation": "",
  "It converges to the exact value of the definite integral": "",
  "It diverges to infinity": "",
  "It approaches zero": "",
  "As n -> infinity (and Delta x -> 0), the Riemann sum approaches the definite integral. This is the formal definition of the integral.": "",
  "What are the 'limits of integration'?": "",
  "The lower bound a and upper bound b in the integral from a to b": "",
  "The maximum and minimum of the function": "",
  "The limits as x approaches a value": "",
  "Limits of integration are the endpoints a (lower) and b (upper) that define the interval over which we integrate.": "",
